---
alwaysApply: true
---

Repo-first: Before coding, use semantic search to find existing patterns for DI, logging, configuration, HTTP, options, and testing in this repo. Prefer matching existing conventions over “best practice”.

Docs for APIs: If you’re unsure about a .NET / ASP.NET Core / EF Core / MS.Extensions API, use Context7 before writing code (especially for DI lifetimes, HttpClientFactory, logging, options, minimal APIs, and hosting).

Local model lane: Use Ollama only for (a) draft implementations, (b) bulk edits, (c) unit/integration tests, (d) refactor proposals. Treat its output as a draft and validate against repo usage + Context7.

Project integrity: Never introduce new packages unless asked. If you do, explain why and update the relevant .csproj.

Compilation gate: After changes, run (or instruct me to run) dotnet test. If tests are slow/unavailable, at minimum run dotnet build.

Modern C#/.NET 9: Prefer file-scoped namespace, required where appropriate, and modern pattern matching. Don’t overuse clever language features; optimize for readability.

No hidden magic: If you change DI registrations, configuration binding, or HTTP pipeline, explicitly list what you changed and why.

Error handling: Avoid swallowing exceptions. Use ILogger<T> and structured logging; don’t log sensitive values.
